[[Field marshal (United Kingdom)|Field Marshal]] '''John Byng, 1st Earl of Strafford''' {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|GCB|GCH|PCi}} (1772 – 3 June 1860) was a [[British Army]] officer and politician. After serving as a junior officer during the [[French Revolutionary Wars]] and [[Irish Rebellion of 1798]], he became Commanding Officer of the Grenadier Battalion of the [[Scots Guards|3rd Regiment of Foot Guards]] during the disastrous [[Walcheren Campaign]]. He served as a brigade commander at the [[Battle of Vitoria]] and then at the [[Battle of Roncesvalles (1813)|Battle of Roncesvalles]] on 25 July 1813 when his brigade took the brunt of the French assault and held its position for three hours in the early morning before finally being forced back. During the [[Hundred Days]] he commanded the 2nd Guards Brigade at the [[Battle of Quatre Bras]] in June 1815 and again at the [[Battle of Waterloo]] later that month when light companies from his brigade played an important role in the defence of [[Hougoumont|Château d'Hougoumont]]. He went on to be [[Commander-in-Chief, Ireland]] and, after leaving Ireland in 1831, he was elected as [[Whigs (British political party)|Whig]] [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Poole (UK Parliament constituency)|Poole]] in [[Dorset]] and was one of the few military men who supported the [[Reform Act 1832|Reform Bill]], for which he was rewarded with a [[peerage]].

==Early years==
Born was the third son of Major George Byng (son of [[Robert Byng (18th-century MP)|Robert Byng]]) and Anne Byng (née Conolly, a maternal granddaughter of the [[Thomas Wentworth, 1st Earl of Strafford|1st Earl of Strafford]] of the first creation), Byng was educated at [[Westminster School]].<ref name=odnb>{{cite ODNB|id=4264|title=John Byng, 1st Earl of Strafford|last=Stephens|first=H.M.|accessdate=2 February 2014|year=2004}}</ref> He was commissioned as an [[Ensign (rank)|ensign]] in the [[Duke of Wellington's Regiment|33rd Regiment of Foot]] on 30 September 1793<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=13589|supp=|startpage=974|date=2 November 1793|accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref> and was promoted to [[lieutenant]] on 1 December 1793<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=13628|supp=|startpage=192|date=1 March 1794|accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref> and to [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|captain]] on 27 December 1794.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=13734|supp=|startpage=1259|date=23 December 1794|accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref> He was sent the [[Netherlands]] later that year and was wounded during a skirmish at [[Geldermalsen]] in January 1795 during the [[Flanders Campaign]].<ref name=heath63>Heathcote 1999, p. 63</ref>

Byng became [[aide-de-camp]] to General [[Richard William Howard Vyse|Richard Vyse]] in the Southern District of [[Ireland]] in 1796 and was wounded during the [[Irish Rebellion of 1798]].<ref name=heath63/> He became a [[major]] in the [[King's Royal Rifle Corps|60th Regiment of Foot]] on 28 December 1799<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=15216|supp=|startpage=1331|date=24 December 1799|accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref> and a [[lieutenant-colonel]] in the 29th Regiment of Foot on 18 March 1800.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=15239|supp=|startpage=260|date=15 March 1800|accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref> He transferred to the [[Scots Guards|3rd Regiment of Foot Guards]] on 11 August 1804<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=15726|supp=|startpage=953|date=7 August 1804|accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref> and took part in the expedition to [[Hanover]] in 1805, in the [[Battle of Copenhagen (1807)|Battle of Copenhagen]] in August 1807 and, having taken command of the Grenadier Battalion of his Regiment, in the disastrous [[Walcheren Campaign]] in Autumn 1809.<ref name=heath63/>

==Napoleonic Wars==
Promoted to [[colonel]] on 25 July 1810,<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=16390|supp=|startpage=1094|date=24 July 1810|accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref> Byng went to Spain in September 1811 to become Commander of a brigade serving under General [[Rowland Hill, 1st Viscount Hill|Rowland Hill]].<ref name=heath63/> Promoted to [[major-general]] on 4 June 1813, Byng commanded his brigade at the [[Battle of Vitoria]] in June 1813 and then at the [[Battle of Roncesvalles (1813)|Battle of Roncesvalles]] on 25 July 1813 when his brigade took the brunt of the French assault and held its position for three hours in the early morning before finally being forced back; meanwhile General [[Lowry Cole]] rushed up reinforcements in the early afternoon and then fended off the French until the evening when thick fog rolled in.<ref>Chandler 1979, p. 384</ref> Byng's stubborn resistance at Roncesvalles allowed the [[Arthur Wellesley, 1st Duke of Wellington|Marquess of Wellington]] to consolidate enough troops to defeat the French at the [[Battle of the Pyrenees]] over the next few days.<ref name=odnb/>

Byng also fought at the [[Battle of Nivelle]] in November 1813 and then at the [[Battle of the Nive]] in December 1813; at the latter battle he led his troops up a hill under fire, occupied it and then planted the colour of the [[31st (Huntingdonshire) Regiment of Foot|31st Regiment of Foot]] there before driving the French troops down the hill. His conduct  was such that the [[George IV of the United Kingdom|Prince Regent]] told him that he was {{quote|"permitted to wear over the arms of the family of Byng, in bend sinister, a representation of the colour of the 31st regiment of foot," and the following crest of honourable augmentation, viz. "out of a mural crown an arm embowed, grasping the colour of the aforesaid 31st regiment, and pendent from the wrist by a ribband the gold cross presented to him by His Majesty's command, as a mark of His royal approbation of his distinguished services".<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=17037|supp=|startpage=1358|date=8 July 1815|accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref>}}

Byng went on to fight at the [[Battle of Orthez]] in February 1814 and at the [[Battle of Toulouse (1814)|Battle of Toulouse]] in April 1814.<ref name=heath63/> During the [[Hundred Days]] he commanded the 2nd Guards Brigade at the [[Battle of Quatre Bras]] in June 1815 and again at the [[Battle of Waterloo]] later that month when light companies from his brigade played an important role in the defence of [[Hougoumont|Château d'Hougoumont]].<ref name=heath63/> After the battle he was placed in command of the [[Order of battle of the Waterloo Campaign#I Corps 2|I Corps]], and took part in the advance on [[Paris]].{{sfn|Siborne|1848|p=689}} Having captured the [[Péronne, Somme|Péronne]] and its fortress,{{sfn|Siborne|1848|p=689–690}} the Corps went on to occupy the heights of [[Montmartre]] and then forming part of the Army of Occupation.<ref name=heath64>Heathcote 1999, p. 64</ref> He was appointed a [[Order of the Bath|Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath]] on 2 January 1815<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=16972|supp=|startpage=19|date=4 January 1815|accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref> and a Knight of the Austrian [[Military Order of Maria Theresa]] on 8 October 1815.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=17075|supp=|startpage=2186|date=31 October 1815|accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref>

==Ireland and politics==
[[File:Wellington at Sorauren.jpg|thumb|right|300px|The [[Battle of the Pyrenees]]: Byng's stubborn resistance at Roncesvalles allowed the [[Arthur Wellesley, 1st Duke of Wellington|Viscount Wellington]] (shown on horseback in the painting) to consolidate enough troops to defeat the French at the Battle of the Pyrenees]]
Byng became General Officer Commanding the [[Eastern Command (United Kingdom)|Eastern District]] in England in October 1815<ref>David R. Fisher and Stephen Farrell, [http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1820-1832/member/byng-sir-john-1772-1860 BYNG, Sir John (1772–1860), of 6 Portman Square, Mdx. and Bellaghy, co. Londonderry] in ''[[The History of Parliament]]: the House of Commons 1820–1832'', ed. D.R. Fisher, 2009</ref> before transferring to be General Officer Commanding the [[Northern Command (United Kingdom)|Northern District]] in England in June 1816.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=hLW6BwAAQBAJ&pg=PA327&lpg=PA327&dq=Command+%22Northern+District%22+1816&source=bl&ots=C0CGjEApKc&sig=Xj0rl8J90tvxBPHbES6Oy9u_bok&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjaorOS4ujJAhUGThQKHaHhDVoQ6AEINzAF#v=onepage&q=Command%20%22Northern%20District%22%201816&f=false|title=The Book of Fallacies|first=Jeremy |last=Bentham|page=327|publisher=Oxford University Pres|year=2015|isbn= 978-0198719816}}</ref> At the [[Peterloo Massacre]] of 1819, he was absent because he had two horses running at York that day, and delegated command to his deputy, who failed to control the dangerously large crowd.<ref>Reid, p. 138</ref> Promoted to [[lieutenant general]] on 27 May 1825,<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=18141|supp=|startpage=925|date=28 May 1825|accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref> he was advanced to [[Order of the Bath|Knight Grand Cross of the Order of the Bath]] in 1828.<ref name=heath64/> He became [[Commander-in-Chief, Ireland]] and was admitted to the [[Privy Council of Ireland]] later that year.<ref name=heath64/> After leaving Ireland, he was elected as [[Whigs (British political party)|Whig]] [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Poole (UK Parliament constituency)|Poole]] in [[Dorset]] in October 1831<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=18859|supp=|startpage=2083|date=11 October 1831|accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref> and was one of the few military men who supported the [[Reform Act 1832|Reform Bill]].<ref name=heath64/> He was also appointed to the honorary position of [[Governor of Londonderry|Governor of Londonderry and Culmore]] on 15 June 1832.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=19066|supp=|startpage=1347|date=12 July 1833|accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref> As recognition of Byng's support over the Reform Bill the [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]], [[William Lamb, 2nd Viscount Melbourne|Lord Melbourne]], raised him to the [[peerage]] as '''Baron Strafford''' of [[Harmondsworth]] on 8 May 1835.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=19268|supp=|startpage=900|date=8 May 1835|accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref> Promoted to full [[general]] on 23 November 1841,<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=20044|supp=|startpage=3007|date=24 November 1841|accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref> he was raised further in the peerage as '''Earl of Strafford''' and '''Viscount Enfield''' on 28 August 1847.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=20769|supp=|startpage=3162|date=31 August 1847|accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref> He also inherited [[Wrotham Park, Hertfordshire|Wrotham Park]] from his eldest brother in 1847.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hertfordshire-genealogy.co.uk/data/places/places-b/barnet/barnet-wrotham-park.htm |title=Wrotham Park, Barnet|publisher= Hertfordshire Genealogy|accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref>

Byng also served as honorary colonel of the [[West India Regiment|4th West India Regiment]], as honorary colonel of the [[West India Regiment|2nd West India Regiment]]<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=17840|supp=|startpage=1275|date=3 August 1822|accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref> and as honorary colonel of the [[29th (Worcestershire) Regiment of Foot|29th Regiment of Foot]];<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=18439|supp=|startpage=238|date=5 February 1828|accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref> in his final years he was also honorary colonel of the [[Coldstream Guards]].<ref name=heath64/> He was promoted to [[Field marshal (United Kingdom)|field marshal]] on 2 October 1855<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=21792|supp=|startpage=3652|date=2 October 1855|accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref> and died at his home in [[Grosvenor Square]] in [[London]] on 3 June 1860.<ref name=heath64/>

==Family==
In 1804 Byng married Mary Mackenzie and they had one son.<ref name=heath63/> Following the death of his first wife, he married Marianne James (daughter of [[Baron Northbourne|Sir Walter James James]]); they had a son and three daughters.<ref name=heath63/>

After his death, Byng was succeeded in the earldom by his eldest son, [[George Byng, 2nd Earl of Strafford]].

